In addition, the suppression of this multiplication has the effect of developing what are called resistant viruses to which drugs no longer have an effect.
The work of experts from three institutions, the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic, the V<0xC5><0xA0>CHT Prague and the University of Heidelberg paves the way for a way to cope with the resistance of the virus.
They have shown that substances called metallocarbons act on the protein responsible for the multiplication of the HIV virus.
Metalocarbons are a combination of boron, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
This combination blocks the development of the virus in a different way from all drugs used so far and that is why they could overcome the problem of resistance.
The work of the researchers leads them to discover new "improved" substances, based on their knowledge of the molecular mechanics of their bonds on the proteins of the virus.
The metallocarbons have a unique three-dimensional structure: two multi-walled cages are formed by the boron, hydrogen and carbon atoms and connected by a metal atom, in this case cobalt.
A treacherous and resistant virus.
HIV protease is a protein of the HIV virus that is essential for the life cycle of the virus.
Without the division of the HIV virus caused by the HIV protease, no mature infectious particles of the virus would have been born.
If HIV protease is stopped, it will also stop the spread of the virus in the patient's body, the researchers explain in a press release published by the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry of the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic.
In their work published in the Journal of Medicinal Chemistry, scientists describe a series of combinations in which two pairs of cages (see table) are connected by a short organic chain, which is then systematically modified.
A little weaker but more reliable.
The efficacy of this series of substances on HIV proteases has been tested in test tubes as well as in its resistant variants, obtained from HIV-contaminated patients.
On the current version of the enzyme, the effect of metallocarbons is not as strong as on clinical drugs, however, it does not weaken on resistant versions to which the current drugs are often ineffective.
The metallocarbons, with their unique mechanism of action and their other properties such as biological and chemical stability, their low toxicity and the possibility of other chemical modifications are therefore interesting combinations to be examined further in order to go towards the development of drugs effective against HIV, says Pavlina de <0xC5><0x98>ezá<0xC4><0x8D>ová's biochemical and laboratory science department.
