To support his approach, he received the support of MEP Hervé de Charette (former UMP former NC) who claimed ownership of the UDF trademark for being the first to file it in 2004 at the National Institute of Industrial Property.
But Friday night, the UDF office, controlled by the friends of François Bayrou who do not intend to let themselves be dispossessed, came out of its silence to launch a warning to the minister and the MP, summoning them to no longer use the acronym and to pass on to them the ownership of the trademark.
You have multiplied, in recent days, the statements indicating that you would propose to your political movement to retake the acronym UDF, wrote the association in a letter signed by 19 of the 24 members of the bureau, including François Bayrou and Marielle de Sarnez du MoDem, as well as Senator Jean Arthuis of the Alliance centriste.
You also thought it was good to keep track of your militant material and on the page of your site, the name of this movement, the +New Center+, the slogan +Today's UDF+, also note the signatories of the mail.
As you do not know, you have no right to use this acronym, explains the UDF office, which warns the NC to "immediately remove the mention of the UDF name from any media as well as from (its) website".
He also asks Hervé de Charette "to pass on the ownership of (the) trademark to its legitimate rights holders".
If you did not, the courts would be seized to enforce the law and the legitimate rights of UDF members, warn the signatories.
In their letter, they specify that the UDF "has been a full political movement since 1978" and recall that Mr. Morin and his friends had "made the choice" to leave him in 2007 "to create a competing movement, as others had done in 2002, to create the UMP".
According to them, the New Centre has no right to use the acronym UDF (Union for French Democracy).
They also recall that the last congress of the UDF voted in 2007 its membership in the MoDem for three years and the creation of an office charged with defending the "material and moral interests" of the formation founded by Valéry Giscard d'Estaing.
As for Hervé de Charette, the office continues, "when he filed the trademark", he was "no longer a member of the UDF for three years", but at the UMP.
He scandalously and fraudulently takes advantage of the absence of filing the acronym UDF to perform it on his behalf.
This indelicacy is turning into a crime, they denounce, before ironizing on the NC strategy: "It seems to us that in politics, as in life, it is more worthy to make a name for oneself than to try to get out of anonymity by fraudulently taking a name to which one is not entitled".
Liliane Bettencourt case: François-Marie Banier to be tried for abuse of weakness
The court of Nanterre decided on Friday to judge the artist François-Marie Banier in order to determine, if, as accused by the daughter of billionaire Liliane Bettencourt, he took advantage of a state of weakness of the octogenary for the plunder of a part of his fortune.
The 62-year-old photographer, known for his star photos, will be tried on April 15 and 16, 2010 for abuse of weakness, a crime punishable by a maximum of three years in prison and a fine of <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>375,000.
This decision means that there will be a trial in this case worthy of a saga about one of the richest families in France, in which mother and daughter tear themselves apart while holding the reins of the L'Oréal cosmetics empire.
But the 15th Correctional Chamber also ordered that a medical expertise of 87-year-old Liliane Bettencourt should be conducted collegiately by three doctors.
The heir and main shareholder of L'Oréal has always refused to undergo such a review, at least not under the conditions proposed by the Nanterre Public Prosecutor's Office during the investigation.
The doctors appointed on Friday will have to submit a report before March 10, 2010, stating in particular whether Liliane Bettencourt was able to find herself in a state of weakness and at what periods.
I think she'll submit.
I'll talk to her about it," Mrs Bettencourt's lawyer, Georges Kiejman, said at the end of the hearing.
Françoise Bettencourt-Meyers' lawyer, Olivier Metzner, welcomed the court's decision.
This is excellent news (...) The expertise will show that he (Mr Banier) has manipulated this elderly lady that we must protect, he said.
For the past two years, Liliane Bettencourt's only daughter has filed criminal charges against François-Marie Banier, a photographer and artist who she accuses of taking advantage of her mother's weakness for years to obtain a billion euros of donations, in the form of checks or contracts.
For her part, Liliane Bettencourt has always denied having been manipulated by the photographer, whom she considers a long-time friend.
While the court was due to examine the admissibility of the action initiated by Ms Bettencourt-Meyers, lawyers' pleas sometimes turned to the large family unpacking on Friday.
Thus, Liliane Bettencourt's lawyer reported three letters sent by her client (in 1999, 2003 and 2005) to her notary, in which she said she was suspicious of Françoise Bettencourt-Meyers' husband.
In the 2003 letter, Liliane Bettencourt added, according to the lawyer: "Could you explain to my daughter that I wrote to Banier once, twice a day for fifteen years.
I haven’t been able to talk to her since her marriage.”
For its part, the Nanterre Public Prosecutor's Office once again ruled that the complainant was inadmissible to act, especially since a guardianship judge has in recent days refused to give effect to her request to open a judicial protection procedure for her mother.
Liliane Bettencourt "has full capacity to act in justice, she is not under protection and has no guardian.
No one else has to act in his place," said the prosecutor's representative, Marie-Chrsitine Daubigney.
The court finally decided that it would rule once the trial had taken place on Ms. Bettencourt-Meyers' admissibility.
Management revolution or the end of economic intelligence?
If nothing changes in the governance of major French companies, our struggle for the development of economic intelligence will have been futile.
For more than a decade, the attitude of the management of large companies towards its employees, recalls the position of companies towards consumers before the marketing revolution: it is to make employees adhere to certain "values" from above as it was once thought, to impose on consumers the products of the technicians.
By putting the customer at the heart of the company, the marketing revolution has put the strategies of conquering the markets back in place... although the authoritarian temptation to impose products disconnected from customer preference factors regularly returns!
Demobilization of employees can lead to deadly demoralization.
Suicides in France Telecom, PSA or Renault are just the emerging part of a much more general phenomenon that affects executives in particular.
This demobilization seriously undermines the development of all the intellectual functions of the company, including R&D and, moreover, economic intelligence.
Indeed, the IE "requires from all stakeholders (...) a proactive approach and a forward-looking vision"; it requires a commitment on the part of employees that authoritarian management revenues totally contradict.
That is why we are calling for a management revolution that would be to put employees at the center of the company’s concerns as much as the customer.
The relative usefulness of internal opinion polls
Will internal opinion polls – such as the questionnaire submitted by Orange to its employees – encourage this revolution in managerial practices?
Unfortunately, I'm afraid not.
- First of all because I have been able to see that, in the face of a new situation, any structure finally, after many detours, comes to prioritize... what she has always done!
Second, because authoritarianism – one of the pathologies of power – grows in proportion to the importance of its own failures.
- Finally, because most leaders have a simplistic view of human behavior.
From the major schools of engineers, they have a mechanistic interpretation of psychology.
They adopt, for intellectual comfort, the old behaviorist theory, recently reactivated by the US "neurosciences" and widely disseminated, without their knowledge, by the institutes of study and the media.
Thus, by suggesting that it is possible to handle the "levers" (sic) of the engagement of the cadres, a recent survey by Ipsos published in Le Figaro.fr comforts the leaders in a posture of mechanistic governance, unsuitable for the world of today.
Identify and measure mobilization factors
On the contrary, the managerial revolution necessary for the proper functioning of modern enterprises presupposes adopting a finalist vision of human behavior.
It consists in integrating, in any reasoning or governance practice, a fundamental finding: for employees, commitment to the company is only possible if it clearly appears as a means of realizing part of their dreams, ambitions, and projects.
Currently, only studies from the Motif Functional Analysis adopt this conception of employee motivations.
These studies have shown that they judge their company based on a predetermined doxa that allows them, through their perceived image of the company, to evaluate what it offers them to realize their life projects.
By identifying and measuring these mobilization factors, business leaders can control, predict and anticipate their "social performance" and put their human resources management "in place".
They thus create a ground for the concerted development of robust and effective economic intelligence.
Oslo Speech: "Just War" Worth Praising Right to Obama
The American right welcomed the speech delivered on Friday in Oslo by Barack Obama, satisfied that the 2009 Nobel Peace Prize defended the concept of a "just war" against the enemies of the United States.
The Conservatives, who had endorsed the award to Mr. Obama on October 9, applauded the presidential speech this time, along with Sarah Palin, a former vice-presidential candidate in the 2008 election.
“I liked what he said,” Palin, a member of the Republican Party’s right wing, told USA Today, adding that she herself addressed the theme of war “sometimes necessary” in her memoirs that have just been published.
War is, of course, the last thing Americans want to do, but it is necessary.
We need to stop these terrorists all over the place, she said.
Obama, who inherited the two wars of his predecessor George W. Bush in Iraq and Afghanistan, used Thursday in Oslo to justify the use of force, a way to explain his decision to send 30,000 additional soldiers to Afghanistan nine days earlier.
Another opponent of Obama, Newt Gingrich, said the president had done a “very good job” in Oslo.
I found the speech to be really good, said the former Speaker of the House of Representatives, who particularly appreciated the mention of "the existence of evil in the world" in the presidential speech.
In some ways, I found this speech quite historic, said Mr. Gingrich, interviewed on the radio show "The Takeaway".
The former elector, considered by some to be a possible candidate for the Republican nomination for the 2012 presidential election, said he was delighted to see "a leftist president" reminding members of the Nobel Committee "that they would not be free and could not award a peace prize if the use of force did not exist".
For Michael Gerson, former penman of George W. Bush reconverted columnist to the Washington Post, Obama made “a very American speech.”
In addition to presenting himself as a "citizen of the world" as "he always does", "he spoke like an American president", reminding Europeans "that they live in a security bubble that they did not create and that they do not do much to preserve it," said Gerson.
Among the few on the right to be unconvinced, a Bush-era hawk, former U.N. ambassador John Bolton, called the speech "outland, bumpy and uninspired" on the National Review Online site.
On the left of the president, Democratic Representative Dennis Kucinich was alarmed to see Barack Obama justify the use of force.
When one wraps war in the notion of justice, one can easily justify the massacre of innocents, he warned.
The center-left press, however, remained commendable in the President's place.
The Los Angeles Times, while continuing to think that the Nobel Prize was awarded prematurely to Obama, called his speech "superproduction" even for a speaker known for his talent.
Oslo's speech "should serve as a roadmap to guide international decisions against conflict, poverty and oppression," the California daily reported.
Obama “made the right speech,” the New York Times said, judging him “at the same time dark and uplifting.”
Three marathons for a deal that saves Christmas supplies
After three marathon negotiation sessions, road trade unions and TLF, the only employers' organization to remain to the end, reached an agreement Friday night that puts an end to the strike slogan and the heavy threat to Christmas supplies.
At the signing session on Friday evening, the Secretary of State for Transport, Dominique Bussereau, "rejoiced" about this agreement, after several negotiation sessions, which began on Wednesday morning.
After a second night of talks, the negotiators left early Friday morning, hoping to sign the agreement quickly by the end of the morning.
And this even if three employer organizations (FNTR, Unostra, OTRE) had knocked on the door.
But it took more than six hours for a meeting to begin at 11 a.m. for everyone to agree and for the text to be signed at 6 p.m.
The conflict "would have been very detrimental to businesses" and "it was to be feared that it would disrupt the end of the year holidays," Bussereau said.
The text foresees a wage increase of 4% for the lowest wages (in local and regional road transport), and of 2.9% for the highest (international transport).
At the hourly rate, for low-wages, "we go from 8.72 euros to 9.06.
It's not much, but we start from a very long way, explained Patrice Clos (FO).
Either we will give the order to our activists that there are no blockades, no blockades of the supply centers.
But you can always have some reluctants who are not happy, he added.
Philippe Grillot, president of TLF, welcomed "a good deal", although it was "difficult to grant the increases on high wages given the international competition".
According to him, the increases will be on the order of 170 euros monthly for low wages and 100 to 120 euros for the highest.
This is the agreement of common sense and respect for employees, Maxime Dumont (CFDT) said, while Thierry Douine (CFTC) hailed "a historic agreement".
Richard Jaubert (CGT) called it an "acceptable compromise".
The agreement also provides for the revaluation of travel costs of 3%, and the holding of general status of road transport in the first half of 2010, which will include addressing the issue of a 13th month and a modernization of the collective agreement.
Mr. Bussereau recalled that "a reduction of 100 million euros in employer charges" has been the subject of a government amendment to the draft amending Finance Act for 2009, voted in the night of Thursday to Friday by the National Assembly.
The government will ask the Senate to vote "in the same terms".
The signing of TLF allows the agreement to apply firstly to companies belonging to this organization, and secondly, to the whole profession, in the event of an extension by the Minister of Labour.
It will be done “as soon as possible,” said Bussereau.
The opposition of employers' organizations can only delay the process.
The FNTR denounced a "dupes market", as the 100 million euros "had already been promised to the sector to compensate for part of the carbon tax".
The Secretary of State for Transportation has forced us to negotiate in the emergency, not in conclusion of a shared analysis, but to not bother the turkey eaters of the next New Year's Eve, lamented the Unostra.
For the Other, the agreement risks "digging the grave of a very large number of SMEs in the sector in the next 12 months".
RER A: disturbances this weekend, unions dissatisfied with the proposals of the RATP
The disturbances on the RER A, France's largest urban public transport line, will continue over the weekend, while a meeting on Friday on the 2nd day of strike between trade unions and RATP management has left them hungry for their premium application.
