Turkish justice dissolves pro-Kurdish party, heavy decision of consequences
The Turkish Constitutional Court ruled on Friday the dissolution of the country's main pro-Kurdish party, a decision that was immediately followed by demonstrations of anger in the Kurdish community, in the southeast of the country and in Istanbul.
This decision could greatly complicate the task of the government, which has just reached out to the Kurdish community to try to end 25 years of conflict.
The Party for a Democratic Society (DTP) was dissolved because it had become a "foyer of activities detrimental to the independence of the state and its indivisible unity," Court President Hasim Kiliç told reporters after four days of deliberations.
The decision was taken unanimously by 11 judges, while a qualified seven-vote majority was required to pronounce the dissolution, Kiliç said, adding that 37 of the party's executives, including its president Ahmet Türk and MP Aysel Tugluk, were banned from political life for five years.
The judge also announced the lifting of the parliamentary immunity enjoyed by Mr. Türk and Ms. Tugluk and the confiscation of the party's assets by the Treasury.
The DTP has 21 seats in Parliament (out of 550).
Its leaders had warned before the verdict that MPs would leave Parliament rather than sit as unlabeled parliamentarians.
The decision follows proceedings initiated in 2007 by the Prosecutor of the Court of Cassation Abdurrahman Yalçinkaya, who accuses the DTP of obeying the "directives" of the Kurdistan Workers' Party (PKK), considered a terrorist organization by Ankara and many countries.
Many observers believe that the DTP is the legal political showcase for the PKK rebels.
The party, however, says it has "no organic ties" with the PKK but refuses to call it a terrorist organization and calls on the government to negotiate with it.
The court’s verdict comes as the government has just reached out to the Kurdish community by proposing a series of measures to strengthen its rights, to try to tarnish Kurdish support for the PKK and end the conflict.
DTP leaders said a dissolution could lead to an escalation of tensions in southeastern Anatolia, where numerous demonstrations against the detention conditions of PKK leader Abdullah <0xC3><0x96>calan have degenerated into clashes with police in recent weeks.
As soon as justice was announced, a thousand protesters gathered in front of the DTP premises in Diyarbakir, the major city in the southeast, which is mostly Kurdish.
Law enforcement fired tear grenades and used water cannons, while protesters threw Molotov cocktails or stones, with fronds.
Hundreds of people also protested in Istanbul.
After the verdict, Türk said the court’s decision would “deepen despair.”
Turkey cannot solve this issue (Kurdish, ndlr) by banning a party, he told the press.
The government, formed by a party from the Islamist movement, also deplored the decision.
We are in principle opposed to the closure of the parties.
This does not solve anything, Energy Minister Taner Yildiz said.
This decision is a total torpedo to the democratic openness launched by the government, commented political analyst Ahmet Insel.
One can, of course, expect a reaction from the PKK, he added.
On Thursday, the PKK claimed an attack that killed seven soldiers three days earlier in northern Turkey, one of the deadliest in recent months.
The first snow can fall.
What Wolfgang Brauburger wants is a very rigorous winter.
But the head of the road clearance and sandblasting service (FES) says that this is not to bother citizens.
This is simply so that agents can test the vehicle technique and learn how to master them well.
And according to meteorologists, this could well be for this weekend.
More than 300 agents and 120 vehicles stand ready to tackle snow and ice.
The ESF is following a very elaborate plan here.
Mr. Brauburger explains that as soon as it starts to snow on the city of Frankfurt and temperatures fall below zero, large sandblasting vehicles run 20 main routes (called routes A).
This includes high-traffic streets, main arteries, such as the Neue Weg and the Hanauer Landstraße.
Also included are fire access, public transport routes, pedestrian areas and sloping streets such as the Atzelbergstraße.
ESF officers begin their service at three in the morning.
If necessary, the 1040 kilometers of road should be salted with a road foundation that adheres well, in a maximum of 3 hours.
This is why the ESF service starts at 3 a.m. "so that the roads are clear when the daily migration traffic begins".
There or it becomes more difficult, it is when the snow begins to fall at 7:30 in the morning.
This poses problems, says the head of the road clearing and sandblasting service "because no motorist is willing to let the salting vehicles pass".
Then, if it does not snow anymore, we take care of access roads and service roads - such as the Rat-Beil-Straße.
The secondary roads and side streets come last.
Mr Brauburger knows well that this always causes some complaints.
At five o'clock in the morning, the ESF pedestrian team sets out to prioritize clearance of areas and passages deemed dangerous.
As for cycle paths, EDF services are generally unable to deal with them.
Mr. Brauburger states that there is a special service in Frankfurt, which is responsible for monitoring the state of the bridges between 22:00 and 4:30.
As ice forms very quickly on these surfaces, salting vehicles intervene as soon as the temperature drops below 2 degrees.
There are also times when the police resort to this special service in case of need.
The Cradle of Dinosaurs
The Tawa hallae resembled other carnivorous dinosaurs: this biped was about 2 meters long by 1.50m high, its hind limbs were powerful, its elongated skull was provided with sharp and curved teeth, its short arms ended in a sickle claw and it had a long tail.
If this species had lived a few million years later, it would have had nothing exceptional.
But, as Sertling Nesbitt of the University of Texas at Austin and colleagues report in Thursday’s Science magazine, the Tawa hallae is one of the first dinosaurs to have these morphological characteristics.
This animal lived 215 million years ago in New Mexico, which at the time was part of the emerging lands of the supercontinent, the Pangea, and was located towards the equator.
Sertling Nesbitt says that the discovery of the Tawa lights up the evolution of the first dinosaurs.
Indeed, it informs us about the kinship ties, the distribution and the characteristics of the latter.
In 2006, Sertling Nesbitt undertook excavations with other paleontologists on the Gohst Ranch site in northern New Mexico.
Randall Irmis of the Utah Museum of Natural History and a member of the excavation team says that they sometimes found a dozen bones in one day, which is absolutely unique for a sedimentary layer dating back to the Triassic.
Scientists quickly realized that some of these bones belonged to a new species.
The excavations updated the remains of five specimens.
A discovery that confirms theories about the beginnings of the evolution of dinosaurs.
The researchers named it Tawa after the Hopi Indian word for the sun god.
For Sterling Nesbitt, this is an exceptional discovery: dinosaur fossils from the Triassic are extremely rare and are limited to a few fragments of incomplete bones.
Not all paleontologists share this enthusiasm.
For example, Martin Sander of the University of Bonn does not find this discovery particularly spectacular, however, he states that it confirms some theories about the beginnings of the evolution of dinosaurs.
According to the current state of knowledge, dinosaurs appeared on Earth about 230 million years ago.
However, most of the oldest fossils are fragmented and incomplete, making it very difficult to classify the first dinosaurs.
Experts wonder, among other things, at what time the saurians divided themselves into three major groups of evolution: the theropods (carnivores) which include the tyrannosaur and the velociraptor that appeared later and from which descend the birds, the sauropods, quadrupeds along the neck, and those that are related to them are the trivore part of which are the trivore and the herbial ones.
According to the studies of S. Nesbitt and his colleagues, the Tawa is one of the first theropods.
This species has an interesting relationship of both primitive and developed characteristics, says S. Nesbitt.
Researchers have found clues that suggest that the Tawa hallae possessed small airbags in its bones at the level of the skull, just like birds that are the descendants of theropods.
These small air pockets make it easier for birds to breathe compared to mammals.
It seems that in the Tawa hallae, the vertebrae were also partially filled with air.
According to Randall Irmis, the Tawa is one of the oldest theropods with small airbags in its bones.
Since the related lineage of the immense sauropods also possessed airbags and a lightweight body, it can be thought that their common ancestor already had this beneficial innovation.
Three successive waves of migration to North America.
Since the earliest known dinosaurs lived in South America, the researchers concluded that the saurians had appeared there.
As a result, the three major lines of evolution split and spread from South America to the rest of the world, i.e. the whole of the emerging lands that formed the Pangea supercontinent.
This seems to be confirmed by the fact that the team of paleontologists also discovered the remains of two other theropods that are not particularly related to it.
The three species cannot descend from a common ancestor who would have migrated, the researchers say.
Alan Turner of the New York Museum of Natural History and co-author of Science Studies magazine says there would have been at least three waves of migration to North America.
There are, of course, some contradictions.
Martin Sander, a paleontologist in Bonn, says there is an even older species, the silesaurus, which lived in present-day Poland and belongs to a group related to dinosaurs.
According to him, this could give a wrong view because there are a large number of dinosaur fossils in South America that have been preserved while virtually none are found on other continents.
On the other hand, how dinosaurs managed to become the dominant tetrapods of the secondary era when they came from a relatively rare collateral line of the reptile branch remains a mystery to this day.
At the time of the Triassic, dinosaurs shared their habitat with many other reptiles, such as with the ancestors of current crocodiles and with many other Saurians.
Towards the end of the Triassic, the dinosaurs spread across the planet, thus fostering the development of many new species, while others, which were related to them, disappeared between the Triassic and Jurassic.
Such a success, however, is not eternal.
To explain this transformation, Martin Sander sees two hypotheses.
There may have been a massive extinction at which dinosaurs randomly survived while other reptiles would have disappeared.
Or else, the dinosaurs were better suited and so they were able to eliminate the competition on the ground.
In any case, such a success is not eternal.
150 million years later, the fall of a meteorite favored the flourishing of a group of animals that had also developed during the Triassic and that since then was vegetation in the shadows: they were mammals.
Solidarity from Vienna to Sao Paulo
The list is long and there are signatories from all over the world.
There are those of professors from the University of Toronto, the University of Cambridge, the University of Vienna or the University of Berkeley in California.
There are those of lecturers from the University of Naples, Quebec, Edinburgh, New York, Sao Paulo, Berlin or Bremen.
The police evacuation of the J.W. Goethe University casino in Frankfurt is making waves around the world.
278 professors and teachers from J.W. Goethe University as well as other higher education institutions in Germany, Europe and North and South America express their solidarity with the protesting students of the Westend Campus.
In a statement written in German and English theycondemn the intervention of the police demanded by the university's steering committee.
Last week, University President Werner Müller-Estler ordered the evacuation of buildings occupied by students and teachers on strike after walls and works of art were painted with graffiti.
Five students were injured in the evacuation.
The signatories consider that the degradations did not justify "such a violent intervention by the police commando against students and teachers who had organized their own classes".
Evacuation is an "unacceptable" violation of freedom of research and education.
Focusing attention exclusively on acts of vandalism serves only to "delegitimate and criminalize the protest" and tries to make the reasons for the mobilization forgotten.
The University's Steering Committee has thus avoided debates that would nevertheless be indispensable.
Law enforcement officers require that criminal proceedings initiated be immediately suspended.
The majority of the occupants did not participate in the degradation.
Legitimation of protests
The youth of the Verdi trade union in the service sector and the German Confederation of Trade Unions (DGB) show solidarity with the students.
The protests are just a legitimate expression of growing concern for our own future, says Alexander Klein, regional secretary of the Verdi youth union.
As for the Minister of Science of the Land of Hesse Eva Kühne-Hörmann (CDU), she took action for the action undertaken by the President of the University and the police.
We thank the President of the University.
Any occupation and degradation of the sites is totally unacceptable, she told the Wiesbaden regional parliament on Thursday during the TV show Aktuelle Stunde.
We understand the meaning of the protests but do not accept vandalism, said the CDU member of the regional parliament Peter Beuth.
The SPD opposition parliamentary groups, the Greens and the Left (the Left) did not share this view.
The CSU takes the pretext of a few painted walls to criminalize the protests, said Janine Wissler of the Left Party (Linke)
Instead of reflecting on the students’ arguments and claims, they are evacuated.
The Left Party has filed a motion summoning the Minister of the Interior to submit a report on the conditions of police intervention.
The new “Silicon-valley”
For a long time it had the reputation of a secret city, forbidden to Western visitors.
Zelenograd, one of the ten districts of Moscow, was, under the Soviet regime, a place of secret weapons research, under strict surveillance.
Today, with its 216,000 inhabitants 37 km from the center of Moscow, the municipality has the reputation of being the Soviet "Silicon Valley".
There are important production and research sites in micro- and nanoelectronics.
Since September 2008, representatives from Zelenograd have established links with Riedberg, the place of the Frankfurt sciences – with the academic institutes and companies of the Frankfurt Innovation Centre (FIZ).
There were mutual meetings and last Wednesday representatives of Zelenograd and Riedberg ratified a “Protocol of Close Collaboration”.
The signatories were the Deputy Mayor of Moscow Yuri Rosljak and the Prefect Anatoly Smimov of Zelenograd for the Russian delegation, Edwin Schwarz head of the project section for Frankfurt.
In 2010, representatives of the FIZ and SMEs, whose strength is scientific research, will go to Zelenograd for a seminar.
Scientific exchanges
This is a sustainable scientific exchange.
