The worlds of the dream
Some see, all awake, images and hear voices that no one else sees or hears.
It is not only in the mentally ill, or under the influence of drugs, that the boundaries between imagination and reality confuse.
As long as these phenomena manifest themselves during sleep, everything is fine.
When we lie in our dark rooms, we can unhinderedly indulge in the wildest dreams and fantasies.
However, he who, awakened, experiences a dream state, hears and sees things that others do not perceive, quickly has the reputation in our Western world of being crazy or drugged, or at least of being an original.
Such images and voices do not appear only in psychiatric patients or under the influence of drugs.
It is our imagination that is at stake: it is the same neural activity that allows us to design houses, paint paintings or write novels, but that sometimes incites the boundaries between dream, madness and reality to merge.
A conscious state of awakening, taking the form of a dream, can present itself in the most diverse forms, at best it is called visions, at worst madness.
But even if the trigger and effect differ, the visions of the mystic Hildegard von Bingen, the drug experiences of the New Age prophet Carlos Castaneda, the secondary states of shamans, psychoses and hallucinations are attributable to very similar processes.
There are hallucinations or delusions when the balance of neurotransmitter substances in the brain - primarily dopamine, norepinephrine, serotonin and achetylcholine - is broken and the interaction between different parts of the brain is disrupted.
Complex hallucinations and delusional thoughts very often manifest during schizophrenic psychosis.
The force of earthly attraction no longer has power over the person.
Since ancient times, philosophers and doctors have always looked at the relationship between madness and dreaming.
For Aristotle, hallucinations were a form of awakened dreaming; Wilhelm Griesinger, one of the founders of modern psychiatry, found in 1861 "a great resemblance between madness and dreaming", for Sigmund Freud the dream was even "a psychosis with all the irregularities, imaginations, delusions and sensory illusions that the composing".
We are in the fall of 2001 when Henning T turns into a comic book character.
His body is in two dimensions with crisp colors.
The earthly attraction no longer has power over him, he flies at the edge of the ceiling.
He feels a blow.
Behind him are winged, grimacing devil creatures, their mouths bleed, showing their teeth.
They chase him, kick him with heavy flamboyant boots, throw him against the walls, he feels pain all over the body.
Toning, nasty voices, screaming, coming out of the walls and the radio.
He can no longer bear those voices that insult and humiliate him.
Henning T. pulls two cables from his stereo, actually a loop and attaches it to a hook attached to the ceiling.
He climbs on a baffle and passes the loop around the neck.
He's jumping.
The loop is detached.
Let this be a lesson to you, shout the voices in a choir to rip off his tympanum. "Go to a clinic and get yourself cured!"
Today Henning T. is 40 years old, he has lived six acute psychoses, the last date of 2 years, the first of almost 20 years.
It was triggered by LSD.
The diagnosis: schizo-affective psychosis, paranoid, in addition he is manic-depressive, he takes medications against depression, mania, schizophrenia.
He has learned to live with his illness, he has been married for three years.
During psychosis, I experienced terrible fears and deep despair.
Illusions are a cruel reality.
Approximately one percent of the population suffers from schizophrenia at least once in their life; in psychiatric clinics it is the most common disease after depression.
In a schizophrenia crisis, those affected can no longer distinguish between the inner world and the outer world, they find themselves in a state of hyperexcitation, which can cause them to suffer from hallucinations, megalomania, relational madness or persecution.
It is very common to hear voices—voices that command, comment, or dialogue.
