75% of working mothers have had professional problems due to their maternity
Discrimination at work has increased in recent years, especially for women of the younger generation who want to be mothers.
This is what the study "Women's fertility and professional career in Spain", conducted by the CSIC in collaboration with the Instituto de la Mujer, reveals.
The survey, conducted on 9,737 women aged 15 to 75, leaves no room for doubt: 75 per cent of working mothers saw their professional careers limited due to maternity.
The study indicates that there are many differences regarding the beginning of life as a couple and the number of children, whether the woman is working or not and the type of employment occupied.
Those who do not have an activity outside the home, work part-time or have an unstable job, get married earlier, have their first pregnancy earlier and have more children.
On the other hand, women with stable employment, mainly in the public sector, are pushing back the entry into couple life and early pregnancy, and have fewer children.
Women between the ages of 35 and 49 who have a fixed job have their first child, on average 3.7 years after they have settled in a couple, up from 4.1 in those who work in the public sector. "These data show that women who have a stable job have needed more time in their lives to get it, which has led them to push back the union and the arrival of children.
In addition, the type of employment exercised greatly influences maternity, but less the date of the beginning of common life,” explains CSIC researcher Margarita Delgado.
The level of education is another factor that increases the age gap between women and their first child.
According to the survey, the higher the level of education, the more they get married and have their first child late.
The difference also persists among women of the same generation.
For example, in the 35-49-year-old group, those who completed elementary and higher education were mothers for the first time at 25.1 and 32.1 years on average, respectively.
“Another distinction also appears among women, depending on their level of education.
While those who have completed elementary studies get married and have their first child before finding a stable job, those who have done middle or higher education reverse this program and prioritize obtaining a stable job as a prerequisite for marriage and the arrival of a child,” said Delgado.
