Emergency braking assistance is now compulsory
As has happened with the ABS anti-lock braking system and as will happen with the ESP stability control, emergency braking assistance systems will be a mandatory element on European cars.
They are already mandatory on newly registered passenger cars and light commercial vehicles, while for the rest of the vehicles a period of shortage was fixed until the end of February 2011.
The measure, imposed by the European Union, aims to strengthen pedestrian protection, although by its mode of action it can also help to avoid many rear shocks.
The emergency braking assistant acts by increasing the pressure on the brakes in case of an emergency detected by the system thanks to the kick given by the driver.
But the latter does not always maintain the pressure until the end.
According to a study conducted by car components manufacturer Bosch, one-third of drivers involved in an accident had not been able to press the brake before the collision, and half of them had not taken advantage of its full strength.
Up to 1,100 accidents
The intervention of the aid, on the other hand, requires the maximum of the braking system, reducing the distance that the car needs to stop.
According to an EU study, if all cars were equipped with this type of elements, up to 1,100 fatal accidents involving pedestrians could be avoided each year.
This reduction would be even more important with the popularization of so-called intelligent emergency braking systems: it is estimated that one in four accidents with injured people would be avoided.
In this case, the vehicle is equipped with a system that, thanks to a radar or camera, detects obstacles and warns the driver, in addition to acting slightly on the brakes.
If the driver reacts, he helps by increasing the pressure on the pedal, if necessary.
If it does not react, and although the collision is unavoidable, the device exerts maximum force on the brakes in order to minimize damage.
